Private consumption growth accelerated in the period, while fixed investment rebounded robustly. Meanwhile, exports surged in the quarter, and consequently the external sector had a neutral impact on the overall headline reading, which contrasted the strong subtraction from growth recorded in Q3. Turning to this year, economic growth is likely moderating as the latest wave of Covid-19 cases and elevated inflationary pressures drag on economic sentiment. Consumer confidence dipped for the first time since September in January, while the IHS manufacturing PMI hit the lowest level since November 2020 in the same month. Nevertheless, the economy should continue to grow at a robust pace in the first quarter, aided by upbeat investment levels and government spending.

The resurgent pandemic and the potential for more stringent restrictions remain key downside risks to the outlook. FocusEconomics panelists see the economy expanding 2.8% in 2022, which is unchanged from last month’s forecast, and 1.5% in 2023.
economicDescription.economicOutlook: Activity in the fourth quarter is likely to have improved after Q3’s sharp contraction. An advancing vaccination campaign and a steep reduction in daily Covid-19 cases allowed for the easing of restrictions at the outset of Q4, with consumer sentiment clocking its highest level since before the pandemic in October–December. Moreover, the composite PMI averaged higher in Q4 than in the prior quarter, recording a multi-year high in November. However, the start of 2022 appears less positive, with the outbreak of the Omicron variant pushing daily cases to record levels in January. As a consequence, authorities have imposed quasi-state of emergency measures in a number of key prefectures including Tokyo, leading the PMI to fall into contractionary territory in January amid falling domestic demand. Meanwhile, the government put forward its draft budget to be debated by the lower house in February, with a record JPY 108 trillion (USD 940 billion) in spending plans.

economicDescription.economicForecast: While GDP growth is seen softening this year from 2021’s projected strong rebound, it will remain solid. Stronger growth in private spending will be sustained by a tighter labor market, and brisker export growth will further support activity. Ongoing uncertainty surrounding the Covid-19 pandemic and the evolution of housing prices continues to cloud the outlook. FocusEconomics Consensus Forecast panelists estimate total GDP to grow 3.6% in 2022, which is up 0.2 percentage points from last month’s forecast, and to expand 2.1% in 2023. economicDescription.economicOutlook: Momentum will have cooled in Q4, with GDP contracting in monthly terms in October and November. November’s softer decline was largely due to improving domestic demand, as private and capital spending growth accelerated from October. Meanwhile, the external sector dragged down the overall reading, as exports declined and imports grew. Furthermore, the manufacturing PMI averaged lower in Q4 than in Q3, and business confidence ticked down in the period, although it remained robust. More positively, the unemployment rate dropped to a 21-month low in November. This, coupled with more upbeat consumer sentiment, should have sustained spending in Q4, although mounting price pressures will have capped the overall improvement. In mid-January, the measures reinstated in December to curb the spread of Omicron were eased partially, which should further support consumer spending.

economicDescription.economicForecast: Cooling household spending and investment activity growth should drive a slowdown in GDP growth this year. FocusEconomics panelists project GDP to grow 2.6% in 2022, which is unchanged from last month’s forecast, and 2.1% in 2023.
economicDescription.economicOutlook: The economy seems to have finished last year on strong footing, exhibiting resilience to the fallout of the Omicron wave. Economic activity accelerated in October–November, largely on sturdier industrial production growth, which more than offset a slowdown in the services sector amid cooling retail sales. Moreover, both industrial output and PMI data suggest overall activity remained buoyant in December. Turning to the first quarter of this year, a relatively healthy economic backdrop—the composite PMI rose in January—has been increasingly overshadowed by escalating tensions between Russia and Ukraine, spelling trouble for the country’s business environment. Western countries are reportedly finalizing sanctions that could include economic countermeasures against Russian banks, the country’s sovereign debt and the Nord Stream 2 gas pipeline, among others, in response to a potential attack on Ukraine.

economicDescription.economicForecast: Economic growth should accelerate robustly in 2022 as oil production rises. Moreover, a tighter labor market and pent-up demand will likely keep household spending growing briskly. That said, uncertainty surrounding the ongoing health crisis, geopolitical tensions and volatile oil prices pose downside risks to the outlook. FocusEconomics panelists see GDP growing 5.7% in 2022, which is up 0.1 percentage points from the last month’s forecast. In 2023, the panel sees economic growth at 3.2%.
economicDescription.economicOutlook: GDP growth should have remained healthy in Q4, but likely slowed from the third quarter’s strong reading due to a less favorable base effect. The non-oil private sector PMI matched the previous quarter’s level on average in Q4, pointing to upbeat activity despite some Omicron-related disruptions weighing on production. Meanwhile, annual oil production growth accelerated in the fourth quarter in line with OPEC+’s decision to ease output cuts, which should have kept overall GDP growing at a brisk pace. Turning to Q1 this year, economic growth is seen gaining momentum as oil production continues to pick up. That being said, non-oil sector growth is likely moderating, as suggested by the non-oil private sector PMI hitting the lowest level since October 2020 in January, with some lingering disruptions caused by the Omicron variant weighing on both foreign and domestic demand conditions.

economicDescription.economicForecast: Growth should accelerate this year, amid a short-term boost from loose monetary and fiscal policy stances and pent-up spending following a weak 2021. However, tax hikes and tighter labor market rules will limit the scope of the recovery somewhat, while weak fiscal metrics, high inflation, protracted supply constraints and a slow absorption of EU funds pose downside risks. Our panelists downgraded the outlook again this month and now project the economy to grow 5.5% in 2022, which is down 0.1 percentage points from last month’s forecast, and 3.6% in 2023.
economicDescription.economicOutlook: The pace of economic expansion softened in quarter-on-quarter terms in Q4. A downturn in consumer spending amid the spread of the Omicron variant and surging inflation—despite a decline in the unemployment rate—was chiefly responsible for the slowdown. On the flip side, the expansion in fixed investment accelerated, hitting an over one-year high. Meanwhile, latest data shows that productivity in Q3 was well below pre-crisis levels, while public debt followed its upward trend in November. Additionally, the government recently proposed a hike to social contributions for self-employed workers, while it also reached a deal to tighten labor market rules—both of which could weigh on job creation ahead. On top of that, in January the country’s independent fiscal authority warned the government against the absence of a detailed budgetary plan on the use of EU funds.

Turning to this year, the government has so far avoided new domestic restrictions despite surging Covid-19 cases, which is supporting activity—as suggested by January’s KOF Barometer. Moreover, travel rules were recently relaxed, which should aid tourism.

economicDescription.economicOutlook: The economy will have lost momentum in the fourth quarter. Moreover, the manufacturing PMI moderated notably in the fourth quarter as a whole, while business confidence eased in the period. Furthermore, consumer sentiment deteriorated in December, plunging to an all-time low. Conditions remained challenging at the outset of the first quarter, with the manufacturing PMI retreating further as elevated price pressures suppressed demand and subsequently output growth.
